30
00:01:29,567 --> 00:01:31,523
Well, in that case, I'll be there.

31
00:01:31,687 --> 00:01:34,281
Here's my money.
Better be worth my while.

32
00:01:34,767 --> 00:01:36,359
Oh, look, here comes
Sherry and Dad.

33
00:01:36,527 --> 00:01:38,085
- Duck.
- No, no, it's all right.

34
00:01:38,247 --> 00:01:40,158
- I invited them.
- Sherry's not going to be there

35
00:01:40,327 --> 00:01:42,124
at your benefit is she?
I can stop that check.

36
00:01:42,287 --> 00:01:43,879
Just relax, Niles.

37
00:01:44,167 --> 00:01:47,079
I've come up with rather an ingenious
plan to occupy their evening tonight.

38
00:01:47,447 --> 00:01:50,325
I bought them tickets to an event
that's right up their alley.

39
00:01:50,487 --> 00:01:52,125
God, I was so mortified
buying the tickets,

40
00:01:52,287 --> 00:01:54,517
I paid cash so they
couldn't trace it back to me.

41
00:01:55,527 --> 00:01:57,563
- Sherry, Dad. Hi.
REBECCA: Excuse me, people.

42
00:01:57,727 --> 00:01:59,206
Did somebody leave
some tickets here?

43
00:01:59,367 --> 00:02:01,722
- Oh, Lord. Yes!
- Something called "Nashville on Ice,

44
00:02:01,887 --> 00:02:04,321
- Yes, right here.
- The All-Skating Country Jamboree"?

45
00:02:04,487 --> 00:02:07,081
Yeah, well.
Well, don't look so smug.

46
00:02:07,247 --> 00:02:09,841
You try skating and blowing into
a jug when your heart's breaking.

47
00:02:11,207 --> 00:02:13,596
I can't believe you
scored tickets to that.

48
00:02:13,767 --> 00:02:16,361
You are well-connected
in this town.

49
00:02:16,527 --> 00:02:18,836
Well, yes, actually,
these are a gift for you and Dad.

50
00:02:19,007 --> 00:02:20,884
- Oh, my God.
- I hope you're free this evening.

51
00:02:21,047 --> 00:02:23,402
Well, we are now.
Wow, Frasier, thanks!

52
00:02:23,567 --> 00:02:25,876
Look at this. Rink side!

53
00:02:26,127 --> 00:02:28,402
Niles, what's that on your cheek?

54
00:02:28,567 --> 00:02:29,886
Oh, what?

55
00:02:30,047 --> 00:02:31,526
My lips.

56
00:02:35,887 --> 00:02:37,843
Oh, look at the time.
I have to go.

57
00:02:38,007 --> 00:02:41,317
Oh, it seems like every time
I see you, you're just leaving.

58
00:02:41,487 --> 00:02:44,126
Yes, and I'd love to stay,
but I have my therapy group meeting,

59
00:02:44,287 --> 00:02:46,596
and last time I was late,
the compulsive gamblers

60
00:02:46,767 --> 00:02:48,120
were betting
the passive-aggressives

61
00:02:48,287 --> 00:02:50,517
that they couldn't
make the overeaters cry.

62
00:02:51,647 --> 00:02:53,797
If you wanna wait here,
I'll get us a couple of coffees.

63
00:02:53,967 --> 00:02:55,605
You know how I like it.
Hot and sweet!

64
00:02:55,767 --> 00:02:57,485
Yeah, but how do
you like your coffee?

65
00:02:59,807 --> 00:03:02,765
- Is he always that funny?
- Oh, yes.

66
00:03:04,687 --> 00:03:05,881
Oh.

67
00:03:06,047 --> 00:03:07,560
It's that damn soap dispenser.

68
00:03:07,727 --> 00:03:09,922
I just gave it a good
pump, and splat.

69
00:03:10,087 --> 00:03:12,123
Oh, I'm sorry.
Roz Doyle, my producer.

70
00:03:12,287 --> 00:03:14,403
You haven't met Dad's
<i>inamorata</i> Sherry Dempsey.

71
00:03:14,567 --> 00:03:15,761
- Oh, hi.
- Hi.

72
00:03:15,927 --> 00:03:17,565
I normally look
a lot better than this.

73
00:03:17,727 --> 00:03:20,924
Oh, now, you don't have to be
self-conscious around me, hon.

74
00:03:21,087 --> 00:03:24,159
We all have our bad days
once we pass 40.

75
00:03:25,087 --> 00:03:26,964
It was nice seeing you.

76
00:03:27,527 --> 00:03:29,677
- What did she say?
- Oh, who cares?

77
00:03:29,847 --> 00:03:31,997
It's the least I can do to string
together a few moments

78
00:03:32,167 --> 00:03:33,486
of silence
without her underfoot.

79
00:03:33,647 --> 00:03:36,320
My God, the woman's
practically moved in with me.

80
00:03:36,527 --> 00:03:38,518
What did she say?

81
00:03:38,687 --> 00:03:40,359
Oh, Roz, take heart.
Now come on, listen,

82
00:03:40,967 --> 00:03:42,958
you may not look your best today,
but you know what?

83
00:03:43,127 --> 00:03:46,005
There's a man sitting right over there
who can't keep his eyes off of you.

84
00:03:46,167 --> 00:03:48,920
- Oh, where?
- Right there.

85
00:03:52,447 --> 00:03:53,721
Oh, my God.

86
00:03:53,887 --> 00:03:55,764
That's John Coughlin
from my high school.

87
00:03:55,927 --> 00:03:58,122
Oh, dear God, please
don't let him recognize me.

88
00:03:58,287 --> 00:04:01,120
I swear I'll never leave
the house unbeautiful again.

89
00:04:01,287 --> 00:04:03,323
- Roz?
- Thanks for listening.

90
00:04:04,367 --> 00:04:07,518
Roz Doyle?
It's me. John Coughlin.

91
00:04:08,367 --> 00:04:09,641
Hi, John.

92
00:04:09,807 --> 00:04:12,321
- Look at you.
- Look at you.

93
00:04:12,487 --> 00:04:15,559
I hardly recognized you
with that moustache.

94
00:04:16,167 --> 00:04:18,362
- Roz...
- Oh, Frasier, I'm so sorry.

95
00:04:18,807 --> 00:04:20,923
This is John Coughlin,
Frasier Crane.

96
00:04:21,087 --> 00:04:23,157
- Hello.
- So did you just move to Seattle?

97
00:04:23,327 --> 00:04:24,919
No, I've been here
for a week on business.

98
00:04:25,087 --> 00:04:26,998
Now it's back to Racine.
Remember Marcie?

99
00:04:27,167 --> 00:04:28,759
- Yeah.
- She's getting married Saturday.

100
00:04:28,927 --> 00:04:30,804
- No kidding.
- Well, I'm late for a meeting,

101
00:04:30,967 --> 00:04:33,083
but it was great running into you.
I can't wait to tell

102
00:04:33,247 --> 00:04:35,807
- the whole gang I saw you.
- You don't have to do that.

103
00:04:37,047 --> 00:04:40,198
Frasier, that guy was the
biggest gossip in my hometown.

104
00:04:40,367 --> 00:04:43,677
He saw me with my hair all sweaty
and my sweatshirt full of soap.

105
00:04:43,847 --> 00:04:45,485
Oh, God, what could be worse?

106
00:04:45,647 --> 00:04:47,126
Well, here's a hint.

107
00:04:47,287 --> 00:04:48,959
Got milk?

108
00:04:50,367 --> 00:04:52,039
Oh, my God.

109
00:04:56,887 --> 00:04:59,276
FRASIER: As a rule I'm terribly
nervous hosting these things,

110
00:04:59,447 --> 00:05:01,278
but it seems to be going well,
doesn't it?

111
00:05:01,447 --> 00:05:04,803
Not for me. I haven't made
inroads with a single woman here.

112
00:05:06,287 --> 00:05:07,515
Ooh! Ooh!

113
00:05:08,527 --> 00:05:10,404
What are you doing?
You look nauseated.

114
00:05:10,567 --> 00:05:13,877
That woman is flirting with me.
This is my "I'm available" face.

115
00:05:15,967 --> 00:05:19,164
Well, stop it. My God,
people will think the shrimp are bad.

116
00:05:20,887 --> 00:05:22,878
- All right, which one?
- At 9 o'clock

117
00:05:23,047 --> 00:05:25,197
blond hair, blue dress.
Now 10 o'clock, 11 o'clock.

118
00:05:25,367 --> 00:05:28,006
- Oh, mama, high noon.
- Oh, dear.

119
00:05:28,167 --> 00:05:29,486
I'm sorry, I have to leave early.

120
00:05:29,647 --> 00:05:31,717
I wanted to let you know
what a lovely time I've had.

121
00:05:31,887 --> 00:05:34,321
Well, thank you, Adair.
It was good to see you.

122
00:05:34,487 --> 00:05:37,047
Adair Peck, my brother,
Dr Niles Crane.

123
00:05:37,207 --> 00:05:39,562
- Enchanted.
- Hi.

124
00:05:39,727 --> 00:05:41,285
Are you feeling okay?

125
00:05:42,367 --> 00:05:44,278
Bad shrimp.

126
00:05:47,527 --> 00:05:49,677
I so enjoyed our chat
about Brecht.

127
00:05:49,847 --> 00:05:51,678
I'm just sorry
we didn't get to finish it.

128
00:05:51,847 --> 00:05:53,519
Well, me too.

129
00:05:53,967 --> 00:05:58,404
I never do this, but if you'd like to
give me a call sometime, I'd like that.

130
00:05:58,567 --> 00:06:00,364
You don't have to call me.
Only if you want to.

131
00:06:00,527 --> 00:06:03,087
And we can talk
about other non-Brecht things.

132
00:06:03,247 --> 00:06:05,317
- Of course.
- You see why I never do this.

133
00:06:05,487 --> 00:06:07,921
Well, I'm certainly glad
that you did it with me.

134
00:06:08,407 --> 00:06:10,875
Nice meeting you, Miles.

135
00:06:16,607 --> 00:06:17,926
Dr Crane.

136
00:06:18,407 --> 00:06:20,796
Who's that gentleman over there?

137
00:06:21,247 --> 00:06:23,841
That's Matthew Pinnick, one of
the theatre's biggest benefactors.

138
00:06:24,007 --> 00:06:25,963
Well, I just caught him
back in my bedroom.

139
00:06:26,127 --> 00:06:28,197
Well, I'm sure he just
wandered in there by mistake.

140
00:06:28,367 --> 00:06:30,358
He was trying on my shoes.

141
00:06:33,687 --> 00:06:35,006
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

142
00:06:37,727 --> 00:06:39,524
An interesting piece of information.

143
00:06:39,687 --> 00:06:42,406
Something tells me the theatre's
going to get that new sound system.

144
00:06:42,567 --> 00:06:44,046
KIMBERLY:
Excuse me.

145
00:06:44,247 --> 00:06:47,045
On behalf of the
Seattle Theatre Ensemble,

146
00:06:47,207 --> 00:06:51,041
I would like to thank Dr Frasier
Crane for hosting tonight's benefit.

147
00:06:51,207 --> 00:06:52,845
But before we say good night,

148
00:06:53,007 --> 00:06:56,363
let's try and coax him
into saying a few words.

149
00:07:00,247 --> 00:07:01,965
All right.

150
00:07:06,007 --> 00:07:08,077
Alexander Pope

151
00:07:08,287 --> 00:07:10,084
once wrote...

152
00:07:10,847 --> 00:07:16,126
...that the theatre aspires to wake
the soul by tender strokes of art.

153
00:07:16,287 --> 00:07:18,164
To raise the genius,

154
00:07:18,327 --> 00:07:20,158
and to mend the heart.

155
00:07:21,247 --> 00:07:24,000
I'd like to say that it's my privilege
to help ensure

156
00:07:24,167 --> 00:07:26,681
the survival
of this noble calling.

157
00:07:26,887 --> 00:07:29,321
And, well, thank you all for coming.

158
00:07:29,487 --> 00:07:32,479
And I'll see you opening night
of <i>Run For Your Wife.</i>

159
00:07:39,607 --> 00:07:41,723
Wow, that was terrific.
Are you always this eloquent?

160
00:07:41,887 --> 00:07:43,639
Oh, well, hardly.

161
00:07:43,807 --> 00:07:46,719
My muse, alas,
is somewhat ephemeral.

162
00:07:46,887 --> 00:07:48,559
Well, it sounds
pretty reliable to me.

163
00:07:48,727 --> 00:07:51,002
- Leslie Wellman. We met earlier.
- Leslie. Of course, yes.

164
00:07:51,167 --> 00:07:54,204
Well, I have to run, but...
I hope I'm not being too forward.

165
00:07:54,367 --> 00:07:56,119
I'd love it if you'd give
me a call sometime.

166
00:07:56,287 --> 00:07:58,118
I'd be delighted to.

167
00:07:58,287 --> 00:08:00,721
- Here's my card.
- Thank you.

168
00:08:08,087 --> 00:08:10,157
Was that Natalie Spencer
I just saw you talking with?

169
00:08:10,327 --> 00:08:11,760
As a matter of fact, it was.

170
00:08:11,927 --> 00:08:14,680
I've been admiring her all evening,
so I steeled myself and asked her

171
00:08:14,847 --> 00:08:16,360
- if she might be free next week.
- And?

172
00:08:16,527 --> 00:08:20,998
Well, her lips said, "No."
But her eyes said, "Read my lips."

173
00:08:26,287 --> 00:08:28,005
I suppose you've
come over here to gloat

174
00:08:28,167 --> 00:08:30,158
- because a woman came on to you.
- Oh, no, hardly.

175
00:08:30,327 --> 00:08:31,646
I wouldn't do that sort of thing.

176
00:08:31,807 --> 00:08:34,321
I came over to gloat because
two women came on to me.

177
00:08:35,807 --> 00:08:36,796
Two?

178
00:08:36,967 --> 00:08:39,242
My God, I've never had a night
like this in my entire life.

179
00:08:39,407 --> 00:08:42,205
I'm a babe magnet. I'm catnip.

180
00:08:44,047 --> 00:08:45,685
I think I feel a fur ball coming up.

181
00:08:47,487 --> 00:08:49,955
Tell me your second conquest
wasn't that haughty filly

182
00:08:50,127 --> 00:08:52,721
- in the white dress, Kimberly Egan?
- No, no, your path is clear.

183
00:08:52,887 --> 00:08:55,196
Oh, what's the point?

184
00:08:55,367 --> 00:08:57,437
I can't take another rejection.

185
00:08:57,607 --> 00:08:59,518
Well, Niles, tell you what.

186
00:08:59,687 --> 00:09:02,884
Seeing as how Cupid has so amply
stocked my quiver this evening,

187
00:09:03,047 --> 00:09:04,605
I will try a shot on your behalf.

188
00:09:05,247 --> 00:09:06,805
Oh, God, you're unbearable.

189
00:09:09,767 --> 00:09:11,166
Excuse me.
Kimberly, good evening.

190
00:09:11,327 --> 00:09:13,283
Oh, Frasier,
thank you again for tonight.

191
00:09:13,447 --> 00:09:15,961
- You really are a wonderful host.
- Oh, thank you.

192
00:09:16,127 --> 00:09:17,879
Listen, I don't usually
do this sort of thing,

193
00:09:18,047 --> 00:09:21,562
but there's a gentleman here tonight
who's, well, rather taken with you.

194
00:09:21,727 --> 00:09:26,437
He's a... An eligible doctor,
and he's a bit shy about coming over

195
00:09:26,607 --> 00:09:28,677
and expressing
those interests to you.

196
00:09:28,847 --> 00:09:31,281
Oh, that is so sweet.

197
00:09:31,447 --> 00:09:35,679
Well, you tell your bashful
friend he needn't be so coy.

198
00:09:35,847 --> 00:09:38,407
I'd love to go out
with you sometime, Frasier.

199
00:09:44,047 --> 00:09:45,526
Call me tomorrow.

200
00:09:45,687 --> 00:09:48,485
- Oh, do you know my brother?
- Oh, of course I do.

201
00:09:48,647 --> 00:09:50,603
Nice seeing you again, Miles.

202
00:09:57,847 --> 00:10:01,396
MAN: <i>Anyway, Dr Crane, I've spent</i>
<i>months now sending out resumes,</i>

203
00:10:01,567 --> 00:10:03,205
<i>pounding the pavement,</i>
<i>but nothing.</i>

204
00:10:03,367 --> 00:10:06,359
Well, Doug, it's possible
you're simply going through a dry spell.

205
00:10:06,527 --> 00:10:08,006
You know, it happens to all of us.

206
00:10:08,167 --> 00:10:10,476
Months go by with nothing.
Then completely out of the blue,

207
00:10:10,647 --> 00:10:14,720
you get not one, but three offers
without doing anything.

208
00:10:14,967 --> 00:10:16,798
Not just for any jobs either,
but desirable ones

209
00:10:16,967 --> 00:10:20,357
with ample salaries
and fabulous perks.

210
00:10:21,287 --> 00:10:24,962
Be patient. Finding employment
is much like dating.

211
00:10:25,127 --> 00:10:27,800
Opportunities come along
when you least expect them.

212
00:10:28,527 --> 00:10:31,121
<i>Thanks, Dr Crane.</i>
<i>Actually, dating's the one area</i>

213
00:10:31,287 --> 00:10:32,686
<i>I don't have any problems in.</i>

214
00:10:33,007 --> 00:10:35,202
<i>Right now, I've got two</i>
<i>women interested in me.</i>

215
00:10:35,367 --> 00:10:38,200
Two? Well, that must make
you the envy of...

216
00:10:38,367 --> 00:10:40,244
...most men.

217
00:10:41,527 --> 00:10:46,396
Well, that's all for today, Seattle.
This is Dr Frasier Crane, KACL 780.

218
00:10:47,687 --> 00:10:50,042
All right, you've compared
dating to unemployment,

219
00:10:50,207 --> 00:10:53,722
claustrophobia and bed-wetting.
Is there anything you'd like to tell me?

220
00:10:54,327 --> 00:10:57,000
Ask me if I'm free this weekend.

221
00:10:57,607 --> 00:10:59,916
- Well, obviously...
- Roz, ask me. Come on.

222
00:11:00,087 --> 00:11:03,159
And let me remind you
it is a three-day weekend.

223
00:11:04,607 --> 00:11:07,917
- Are you free this weekend?
- No, I'm not. I have a date.

224
00:11:08,447 --> 00:11:09,562
I have a date tomorrow night.

225
00:11:09,727 --> 00:11:11,683
Oh, and let me check
my calendar for Sunday.

226
00:11:12,327 --> 00:11:14,636
Oh, yes. Another date.

227
00:11:16,167 --> 00:11:17,998
- Not bad.
- Not bad?

228
00:11:18,167 --> 00:11:20,283
If I didn't know better,
I'd say someone was jealous.

229
00:11:20,447 --> 00:11:23,325
After this weekend, you may
have to give up your dating crown.

230
00:11:23,487 --> 00:11:25,523
I once had three dates
on a single Saturday

231
00:11:25,687 --> 00:11:29,396
and still had time to defrost
my refrigerator and rotate my tires.

232
00:11:31,487 --> 00:11:34,001
It's a wonder you could
rotate anything after that.

233
00:11:34,807 --> 00:11:36,877
