00:23:33,447 --> 00:23:34,436
Yes, isn't it.

471
00:23:34,607 --> 00:23:36,404
[IN AMERICAN ACCENT]
Hey, Dr Crane. How's tricks?

472
00:23:36,607 --> 00:23:37,881
[NILES SCREAMS]

473
00:23:39,567 --> 00:23:42,718
- I'm trying my American accent.
NILES: Well, stop it.

474
00:23:42,887 --> 00:23:45,799
I mean... Just that we
Americans are very sensitive

475
00:23:45,967 --> 00:23:47,605
about our crude speech patterns.

476
00:23:47,767 --> 00:23:50,361
[IN NORMAL ACCENT] Oh, I'm sorry.
I didn't mean to offend.

477
00:23:50,527 --> 00:23:52,483
No, no, no.
It's quite all right.

478
00:23:52,647 --> 00:23:54,205
You have a real flair for accents.

479
00:23:54,367 --> 00:23:57,359
Just out of curiosity, have you ever
tried a saucy French chambermaid?

480
00:23:57,527 --> 00:23:58,846
FRASIER:
Niles, no.

481
00:24:01,607 --> 00:24:04,758
Frasier's just been telling me how well
Dad's taking the breakup with Sherry.

482
00:24:04,927 --> 00:24:06,440
Yeah, a little too well,
if you ask me.

483
00:24:06,607 --> 00:24:08,962
Daphne, we've had this
discussion already. He's fine.

484
00:24:09,127 --> 00:24:11,277
DAPHNE: He's in a lot more pain
than he's letting on.

485
00:24:11,447 --> 00:24:13,836
You don't see it because you like
having your apartment back.

486
00:24:14,007 --> 00:24:16,282
Yes. Well, leave the complex
analyses to the professionals.

487
00:24:16,447 --> 00:24:17,800
MARTIN:
Oh, hi, Niles.

488
00:24:17,967 --> 00:24:20,037
You feel like going to the movies
with me and Daphne?

489
00:24:20,207 --> 00:24:21,765
NILES:
Thanks, but I have plans.

490
00:24:21,927 --> 00:24:24,441
Listen, Dad, I'm sorry
to hear about you and Sherry.

491
00:24:24,607 --> 00:24:27,280
Oh, that's all right.
There's nothing to be sorry about.

492
00:24:27,447 --> 00:24:30,280
It's kind of fun to go back to
my old bachelor days, you know.

493
00:24:30,447 --> 00:24:31,675
Yeah, don't worry about me.

494
00:24:31,847 --> 00:24:33,758
Easy come, easy go.
You want a boilermaker?

495
00:24:33,927 --> 00:24:35,838
- No, thanks.
- Oh, well, more for me.

496
00:24:36,007 --> 00:24:38,646
I should pack a few of those
for the movies, you know.

497
00:24:39,047 --> 00:24:40,446
Mr Crane...

498
00:24:40,607 --> 00:24:42,120
Oh, come on.
I'm only kidding.

499
00:24:42,287 --> 00:24:44,596
No. No, it's kind of fun
to laugh at things again.

500
00:24:44,767 --> 00:24:47,201
That was the problem with Sherry.
She had no sense of humour.

501
00:24:47,367 --> 00:24:49,198
Just a real stick
in the mud, you know.

502
00:24:49,767 --> 00:24:51,325
We'd better get going. We'll be late.

503
00:24:51,487 --> 00:24:53,364
I'll get the elevator.

504
00:24:56,927 --> 00:24:59,395
Well, what's your diagnosis now?

505
00:24:59,567 --> 00:25:02,843
It's a clear-cut case
of post-Sherry euphoria.

506
00:25:03,927 --> 00:25:04,962
[BELL RINGS]

507
00:25:05,127 --> 00:25:07,118
Oh, there are my canapës.

508
00:25:07,287 --> 00:25:08,800
Oh, right. Date number two.

509
00:25:08,967 --> 00:25:11,720
I'll be off as well.
You can fill me in tomorrow.

510
00:25:11,887 --> 00:25:14,640
You'll get a full debriefing.
As, hopefully, will I.

511
00:25:18,047 --> 00:25:20,720
All right, young Edward.

512
00:25:20,887 --> 00:25:23,560
Learn from the master.

513
00:25:23,727 --> 00:25:27,242
Now, just follow
these time-honoured traditions,

514
00:25:27,407 --> 00:25:29,875
and you too might get lucky
with that young Pekinese peach

515
00:25:30,047 --> 00:25:31,605
you've been eyeing in the park.

516
00:25:32,247 --> 00:25:34,602
Now, for mood...

517
00:25:35,127 --> 00:25:36,606
...Vivaldi.

518
00:25:37,327 --> 00:25:39,477
And then for lighting...

519
00:25:40,487 --> 00:25:42,762
...not so bright
as to show the wrinkles.

520
00:25:42,967 --> 00:25:45,356
Not so dark as to make
her think you're hiding anything.

521
00:25:45,527 --> 00:25:46,755
And then finally...

522
00:25:46,927 --> 00:25:47,916
[DOORBELL RINGS]

523
00:25:48,087 --> 00:25:51,841
Leaving nothing to chance
Pouilly-Fuissë, 1992.

524
00:25:52,007 --> 00:25:54,567
The nectar of the gods.

525
00:25:57,887 --> 00:25:59,605
Dear God,

526
00:25:59,927 --> 00:26:02,122
I could teach a course.

527
00:26:08,447 --> 00:26:10,563
Adair, come in.

528
00:26:11,007 --> 00:26:13,475
- May I take your coat?
- Oh, thank you.

529
00:26:13,687 --> 00:26:15,598
It's so nice of you
to have me over.

530
00:26:15,767 --> 00:26:18,998
- I hope you didn't go to any trouble.
- Oh, nothing special.

531
00:26:19,167 --> 00:26:20,919
I've got to tell you,
this is all so strange.

532
00:26:21,087 --> 00:26:25,239
I mean, one night I'm at Dr Frasier
Crane's house for a benefit.

533
00:26:25,407 --> 00:26:27,637
And two days later,
I'm back at his house for a date.

534
00:26:27,807 --> 00:26:31,516
If there's one thing I've learned, it's
that life is nothing without spontaneity.

535
00:26:31,727 --> 00:26:33,206
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING]

536
00:26:34,767 --> 00:26:36,758
Come have a look at the city.

537
00:26:37,887 --> 00:26:41,516
ADAIR:
Oh, what a lovely view.

538
00:26:41,687 --> 00:26:43,484
I didn't fully appreciate
it the other night.

539
00:26:44,367 --> 00:26:45,925
My sentiments exactly.

540
00:26:47,967 --> 00:26:49,798
Here, have some wine?

541
00:26:49,967 --> 00:26:51,480
Oh, certainly.

542
00:26:51,807 --> 00:26:53,286
Here we are.

543
00:26:55,287 --> 00:26:56,800
To...

544
00:26:57,447 --> 00:26:59,244
...possibilities.

545
00:27:01,967 --> 00:27:03,719
I wonder if I can see
my apartment from here.

546
00:27:03,887 --> 00:27:07,323
Well, if you can, don't tell me. I have
a telescope, and I am not to be trusted.

547
00:27:09,247 --> 00:27:10,680
Funny, charming.

548
00:27:10,847 --> 00:27:12,519
Next I'm gonna find out
you're a great cook.

549
00:27:12,687 --> 00:27:15,485
Well, don't get your hopes up.
Duck comfit?

550
00:27:16,367 --> 00:27:17,402
[DOORBELL RINGS]

551
00:27:17,567 --> 00:27:19,956
Oh, good Lord.
Excuse me for just a moment.

552
00:27:23,047 --> 00:27:24,400
- Hello, Frasier.
- Sherry.

553
00:27:24,567 --> 00:27:26,683
My father's not here now.
I'll tell him you stopped by.

554
00:27:26,847 --> 00:27:28,758
Wait, wait. I just came by
to pick something up.

555
00:27:28,927 --> 00:27:31,566
Why don't you tell me what it is.
I'll have it messengered tomorrow.

556
00:27:31,727 --> 00:27:34,719
It's my banjo. Can't I have it?

557
00:27:34,887 --> 00:27:36,081
FRASIER:
Well...

558
00:27:36,567 --> 00:27:37,602
All right, all right.

559
00:27:37,767 --> 00:27:40,600
Listen, I'm on a date here.
So you know, just try to make it quick.

560
00:27:40,767 --> 00:27:43,918
- Okay. Hi, how are you?
- She's fine. She's fine. We're fine.

561
00:27:44,087 --> 00:27:45,964
All right, you know
where you're going.

562
00:27:46,127 --> 00:27:48,721
It's my father's ex-girlfriend.

563
00:27:48,887 --> 00:27:50,206
Well, where were we?

564
00:27:50,367 --> 00:27:52,119
I was about to say
that this duck is superb.

565
00:27:52,287 --> 00:27:53,322
Oh, thank you very much.

566
00:27:53,487 --> 00:27:56,684
And the way the wine
complements it and the music...

567
00:27:56,847 --> 00:27:58,803
I'm guessing you entertain often.

568
00:27:58,967 --> 00:28:00,116
Well...

569
00:28:00,287 --> 00:28:03,040
No, actually, I'm really rather lonely.

570
00:28:03,207 --> 00:28:05,675
Tell you what, take my telescope
home. You can see for yourself.

571
00:28:08,327 --> 00:28:09,726
Got my banjo.

572
00:28:09,887 --> 00:28:11,445
FRASIER:
Well, yes, okay. Bye-bye.

573
00:28:11,607 --> 00:28:14,280
Bye, Frasier.
Oh, it was nice seeing you again.

574
00:28:14,447 --> 00:28:16,119
I'm sorry, have we met?

575
00:28:16,287 --> 00:28:18,721
Well, yes, on your date last night.
Kimberly, isn't it?

576
00:28:18,887 --> 00:28:21,196
- No.
- Well, you've got what you came for.

577
00:28:21,367 --> 00:28:22,720
Off you go.

578
00:28:22,927 --> 00:28:26,158
Well, I'm sorry, hon. But she does
look just like the other girl.

579
00:28:26,327 --> 00:28:28,238
Besides, you were playing
the same make-out music.

580
00:28:28,407 --> 00:28:29,920
All right, off you go.

581
00:28:33,687 --> 00:28:35,837
Well, some more wine?

582
00:28:36,407 --> 00:28:38,762
Two dates in two nights
isn't bad for someone who's lonely.

583
00:28:38,927 --> 00:28:41,157
Well, you can hardly call
what happened last night a date.

584
00:28:41,327 --> 00:28:43,079
The woman that organized
the benefit came by.

585
00:28:43,247 --> 00:28:45,556
She just dropped in to say thank you.

586
00:28:45,727 --> 00:28:48,002
Wait a minute.
You mean Kimberly Egan?

587
00:28:48,167 --> 00:28:51,443
- She broke up my first marriage.
- Well, I hardly know the woman.

588
00:28:51,607 --> 00:28:53,518
I mean, she spent
all of ten minutes here.

589
00:28:53,687 --> 00:28:55,245
Look, I'm not going
through this again.

590
00:28:55,407 --> 00:28:58,240
Oh, Adair, listen.
Listen, this is all in your mind.

591
00:28:58,407 --> 00:29:00,284
I mean, we spent one night together.

592
00:29:00,447 --> 00:29:01,721
She means nothing to me.

593
00:29:01,887 --> 00:29:04,560
Gee, where have
I heard that before?

594
00:29:16,727 --> 00:29:17,876
Go ahead.

595
00:29:27,447 --> 00:29:29,244
So for the second time in two nights,

596
00:29:29,407 --> 00:29:31,159
Sherry managed
to chase away another date.

597
00:29:31,607 --> 00:29:35,600
It's like she's a scarecrow
in the cornfield of my love life.

598
00:29:35,967 --> 00:29:38,720
I don't know how many more of
your disastrous love stories I can hear.

599
00:29:38,887 --> 00:29:40,718
I'll say when.

600
00:29:41,087 --> 00:29:42,202
Hello.

601
00:29:42,927 --> 00:29:44,997
You look like an almost-presentable
version of someone

602
00:29:45,167 --> 00:29:47,283
- who works with my brother.
- Bite me.

603
00:29:50,207 --> 00:29:51,526
Oh, it is you.

604
00:29:51,687 --> 00:29:54,759
You haven't seen my high school
friend, John, around here, have you?

605
00:29:54,927 --> 00:29:57,600
Well, no, we haven't, Roz. I suppose
you finally tracked him down?

606
00:29:57,767 --> 00:29:59,598
Yeah. I'm meeting him
here for coffee.

607
00:29:59,767 --> 00:30:02,520
I'm gonna tell him I'm on my way
to a chic cocktail party.

608
00:30:02,687 --> 00:30:04,678
This is the Roz
I want him to talk about

609
00:30:04,847 --> 00:30:06,917
when he goes to that
wedding this weekend.

610
00:30:07,087 --> 00:30:09,203
The vain, neurotic, lying Roz?

611
00:30:10,407 --> 00:30:12,238
- Oh, are you Roz?
- Yeah.

612
00:30:12,407 --> 00:30:14,477
There was a call for you earlier
from a John Coughlin.

613
00:30:14,647 --> 00:30:17,605
He said he's sorry, but he can't meet
you. He had to take an earlier flight.

614
00:30:17,767 --> 00:30:19,200
Oh, great.

615
00:30:19,367 --> 00:30:20,925
- Roz Doyle, right?
- Yeah.

616
00:30:21,487 --> 00:30:24,684
Sorry. You don't look
anything like he described.

617
00:30:25,687 --> 00:30:28,565
All right, before I do anything
crazy like go to the airport,

618
00:30:28,727 --> 00:30:30,319
fly to Wisconsin
and crash a wedding,

619
00:30:30,487 --> 00:30:32,637
did I really look that bad
the other day?

620
00:30:32,807 --> 00:30:34,843
- Hi, guys.
- Oh, hi, Sherry.

621
00:30:35,007 --> 00:30:36,599
Gee, you look familiar.

622
00:30:36,927 --> 00:30:39,361
Did I meet your older sister
in here the other day?

623
00:30:39,527 --> 00:30:42,041
Oh, she must be jealous of you.

624
00:30:44,567 --> 00:30:46,205
ROZ:
Taxi!

625
00:30:49,167 --> 00:30:52,398
- Mind if I join you?
- Well, of course not.

626
00:30:53,527 --> 00:30:56,564
I was hoping I'd catch you here.

627
00:30:57,527 --> 00:31:00,121
Well, I've been thinking about
what happened yesterday

628
00:31:00,287 --> 00:31:03,279
between your Dad and me,
and I just can't figure it out.

629
00:31:03,447 --> 00:31:07,406
One minute we were having
a stupid argument about chopsticks,

630
00:31:07,567 --> 00:31:10,081
and the next minute
we were broken up.

631
00:31:10,247 --> 00:31:12,807
Well, I hate to put you
on the spot like this,

632
00:31:12,967 --> 00:31:15,117
but did he say anything to you?

633
00:31:15,487 --> 00:31:17,239
FRASIER:
Well, not really.

634
00:31:17,407 --> 00:31:20,240
You know how closed-mouth
Dad is. It's just...

635
00:31:20,407 --> 00:31:23,524
Well, he did say that the break-up
was a long time coming.

636
00:31:24,167 --> 00:31:26,727
Oh, now I really am confused.

637
00:31:26,887 --> 00:31:28,684
I mean, I thought everything
was going fine.

638
00:31:28,847 --> 00:31:30,803
Well, better than fine.

639
00:31:31,767 --> 00:31:33,519
The other night,

640
00:31:33,687 --> 00:31:36,406
we both said,
"I love you," for the first time.

641
00:31:36,567 --> 00:31:39,365
- You did?
- Yes.

642
00:31:39,807 --> 00:31:42,844
Oh, it's just that in the past
he's been rather reserved

643
00:31:43,007 --> 00:31:44,406
about expressing himself that way.

644
00:31:45,207 --> 00:31:48,358
Well, I guess he sort
of hesitated before he said it,

645
00:31:48,527 --> 00:31:52,076
but, I mean, a lot of guys do that when
you spring it on them for the first time.

646
00:31:52,247 --> 00:31:54,602
Yes, well, I can certainly understand
why you're confused.

647
00:31:54,767 --> 00:31:56,086
Well...

648
00:31:56,807 --> 00:31:58,763
If you'd like, I could speak
to him on your behalf.

649
00:31:58,967 --> 00:32:01,435
- Ow.
NILES: I'm sorry. Was that your shin?

650
00:32:01,887 --> 00:32:03,525
SHERRY:
No. No, thanks, Frasier.

651
00:32:03,687 --> 00:32:06,599
I don't wanna put you
in the middle of this.

652
00:32:06,767 --> 00:32:08,962
I'm just frustrated.

653
00:32:09,127 --> 00:32:10,765
Listen. Thanks for listening.

654
00:32:10,927 --> 00:32:12,406
- No problem.
- Anytime.

655
00:32:12,567 --> 00:32:17,277
You know, I really thought
I hit the jackpot with Marty.

656
00:32:17,687 --> 00:32:21,885
It isn't easy finding someone
you think the world of.

657
00:32:22,047 --> 00:32:26,199
Oh, I know, you go tomcatting around
with a different girl every night,

658
00:32:26,367 --> 00:32:28,961
but you can't find
happiness that way.

659
00:32:29,687 --> 00:32:31,359
I haven't so far.

660
00:32:36,967 --> 00:32:38,559
Ow!

661
00:32:39,847 --> 00:32:42,600
- I didn't kick you that hard.
- You didn't have to kick me at all.

662
00:32:42,767 --> 00:32:44,598
Were you seriously
considering playing therapist

663
00:32:44,767 --> 00:32:46,519
to Dad and that woman
after we got rid of her?

664
00:32:46,687 --> 00:32:48,484
I have no intention
of repairing the rift.

665
00:32:48,647 --> 00:32:51,605
God. But last night
for the first time in months,

666
00:32:51,767 --> 00:32:53,325
I wasn't jolted awake at 2 a.m.

667
00:32:53,487 --> 00:32:56,126
By her rousing rendition
of "Foggy Mountain Breakdown."

668
00:32:58,447 --> 00:33:01,041
It seems a little odd
that Dad chose to break up

669
00:33:01,207 --> 00:33:03,323
with Sherry just after
he told her that he loved her.

670
00:33:03,487 --> 00:33:06,445
As I recall, she said
he hesitantly said it back to her.

671
00:33:06,607 --> 00:33:09,041
That's a clear picture of a man
who didn't share her feelings.

672
00:33:09,207 --> 00:33:11,163
Yes, well, I think
he does share her feelings.

673
00:33:11,567 --> 00:33:13,762
- He just panicked out of fear.
- Fear of what?

674
00:33:13,927 --> 00:33:16,566
Well, lots of things.
Change. Commitment.

675
00:33:17,047 --> 00:33:18,958
Becoming vulnerable
to somebody again.

676
00:33:20,647 --> 00:33:22,877
I'm afraid he broke up
with her for all the wrong reasons.

677
00:33:23,047 --> 00:33:26,164
Well, if he'd like a list of the right
reasons, it's available on request.

678
00:33:27,487 --> 00:33:29,125
The least I can do
is have a talk with him.

679
00:33:29,287 --> 00:33:31,039
No, the least
you can do is nothing.

680
00:33:31,207 --> 00:33:34,005
Dad hasn't asked for our help.
We should let nature take its course.

681
00:33:34,167 --> 00:33:37,364
It's like one of those wildlife films
with the lion chasing the antelope.

682
00:33:37,527 --> 00:33:41,122
You don't ask why the photographer
doesn't interfere. You just accept it.

683
00:33:41,967 --> 00:33:43,366
As a general rule, Niles,

684
00:33:43,527 --> 00:33:45,722
the photographer
is not related to the antelope.

685
00:33:46,367 --> 00:33:48,517
Obviously, you and I don't
see eye-to-eye on this issue.

686
00:33:49,247 --> 00:33:51,602
- Where are you going?
- I have a date in 45 minutes,

687
00:33:51,767 --> 00:33:54,486
and a bleeding antelope sitting
in a Barcalounger in my apartment.

688
00:33:57,727 --> 00:34:00,639
I suppose that sounded strange
to you. I'd be happy to explain it.

689
00:34:00,807 --> 00:34:03,196
Are you, by any chance,
free at the end of your shift?

690
00:34:03,367 --> 00:34:05,198
Sorry.

691
00:34:05,367 --> 00:34:07,517
I've still got it.

692
00:34:22,887 --> 00:34:25,606
Not so fast, Mr Hicks.

693
00:34:26,887 --> 00:34:29,196
You won't catch me
doing anything foolish.

694
00:34:44,207 --> 00:34:45,526
Daphne.

695
00:34:45,687 --> 00:34:47,006
Hello, Dr Crane.

696
00:34:50,447 --> 00:34:52,642
- Enjoy your evening.
- Yes, you too.

697
00:34:53,207 --> 00:34:56,165
He's been under
a lot of stress lately.

698
00:35:00,767 --> 00:35:02,917
Oh, Dad, listen, I'm glad
you're home. We've gotta talk.

699
00:35:03,087 --> 00:35:04,725
No good conversation
ever started that way.

700
00:35:04,887 --> 00:35:06,320
We have to talk
about you and Sherry.

701
00:35:06,487 --> 00:35:08,239
Why? Look, I'm fine with it.

702
00:35:08,407 --> 00:35:10,363
- Come on, now let it go.
- Dad.

703
00:35:10,527 --> 00:35:11,960
Listen, I spoke with Sherry today.

704
00:35:12,127 --> 00:35:13,606
You did what? What for?

705
00:35:13,767 --> 00:35:15,359
Well, she came to see me.

706
00:35:15,527 --> 00:35:18,246
Said she was a bit confused
about what happened the other day.

707
00:35:18,407 --> 00:35:20,875
Well, from her story,

708
00:35:21,047 --> 00:35:23,402
I think what you're
contending with here

709
00:35:23,567 --> 00:35:26,798
is a classic case of panic
induced by fear of commitment.

710
00:35:26,967 --> 00:35:29,037
You hear that, Eddie?
That's what buys your dog food.

711
00:35:29,207 --> 00:35:32,677
Well, she told me about a little incident
that took place the other evening

712
00:35:32,847 --> 00:35:34,439
where she expressed
her feelings for you,

713
00:35:34,607 --> 00:35:36,563
- and you hesitantly reciprocated.
- Oh, jeez.

714
00:35:36,727 --> 00:35:38,843
She told you about that?
Look, to cut it short,

715
00:35:39,007 --> 00:35:41,282
she told me how she felt about me.
I said it back,

716
00:35:41,447 --> 00:35:43,802
but I only said it
because I felt I had to.

717
00:35:43,967 --> 00:35:45,798
That's not really what I feel.
So end of story.

718
00:35:45,967 --> 00:35:46,956
[DOORBELL RINGS]

719
00:35:47,127 --> 00:35:49,925
Now, there's my date. Listen,
I'm sorry for butting into your life,

720
00:35:50,087 --> 00:35:51,759
but I happen to be
concerned about you.

721
00:35:51,927 --> 00:35:53,246
You may find
this hard to believe,

722
00:35:53,407 --> 00:35:55,682
but your welfare happens
to be very important to me.

723
00:35:59,327 --> 00:36:00,806
[CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING]

724
00:36:03,607 --> 00:36:05,484
- Hi, Frasier.
- Sherry.

725
00:36:09,007 --> 00:36:10,645
- Hi, Martin.
- Hey.

726
00:36:10,807 --> 00:36:13,685
You left your Sinatra tape in my car.

727
00:36:13,847 --> 00:36:15,485
Oh, thanks.
I've been looking for that.

728
00:36:16,247 --> 00:36:17,600
Well, here you go.

729
00:36:20,567 --> 00:36:23,320
- Bye.
- So long.

730
00:36:24,727 --> 00:36:26,957
I saw that, Dad.
I saw the way you looked at her.

731
00:36:27,127 --> 00:36:29,436
You can't convince me you
don't feel the same way about her.

732
00:36:29,607 --> 00:36:32,326
Look, I appreciate what you're
doing, Frasier. I really do. But stop!

733
00:36:32,487 --> 00:36:34,125
All right, fine.
It's your life.

734
00:36:34,287 --> 00:36:36,164
I wouldn't interfere.

735
00:36:36,327 --> 00:36:38,841
Sherry, wait. If you could just stay
for a few minutes,

736
00:36:39,007 --> 00:36:41,965
- I think I can straighten this out.
- It didn't look like he wanted you to.

737
00:36:42,127 --> 00:36:44,277
Yes, he's just being
his old stubborn, ornery self.

738
00:36:44,447 --> 00:36:46,358
- I do miss that.
- All right. I'll go talk to him

739
00:36:46,527 --> 00:36:47,926
You stay here.

740
00:36:49,687 --> 00:36:50,961
- Frasier?
- Oh, Leslie.

741
00:36:51,127 --> 00:36:52,640
Sorry. I'm a little early.

742
00:36:52,807 --> 00:36:55,275
- Way to go, Fras.
- Oh, dear God.

743
00:36:55,447 --> 00:36:56,960
Sherry, this is Leslie.
Leslie, Sherry.

744
00:36:57,127 --> 00:36:58,958
- Leslie, come on in.
- Hi.

745
00:36:59,807 --> 00:37:01,604
Frasier, could I use
the little girl's room?

746
00:37:01,767 --> 00:37:03,166
No. No need to ask.

747
00:37:03,327 --> 00:37:04,680
Come on in.

748
00:37:05,847 --> 00:37:07,246
- May I take your coat?
- Of course.

749
00:37:07,407 --> 00:37:08,920
- Yes, there we are.
LESLIE: Thank you.

750
00:37:09,087 --> 00:37:11,442
Yes, well, you see, Sherry
is my father's lady friend,

751
00:37:11,607 --> 00:37:13,518
and they're going through
a bit of a rough patch.

752
00:37:13,687 --> 00:37:16,247
If you can excuse me, I have
to talk with him for just one minute.

753
00:37:16,407 --> 00:37:18,284
Take your time.
I can always chat with Sherry.

754
00:37:18,447 --> 00:37:21,280
No, no. What, and miss
this fabulous sunset?

755
00:37:21,447 --> 00:37:22,766
Isn't that something?

756
00:37:22,967 --> 00:37:24,195
LESLIE:
Wow.

757
00:37:24,367 --> 00:37:26,642
It's even more stunning
than I remember.

758
00:37:26,807 --> 00:37:28,126
Yes, it is.

759
00:37:29,087 --> 00:37:30,839
Excuse me for a minute.
Oh, no, wait.

760
00:37:31,007 --> 00:37:32,759
Here, some wine?

761
00:37:33,687 --> 00:37:36,360
Here we are. To...

762
00:37:37,087 --> 00:37:39,157
...possibilities.

763
00:37:41,567 --> 00:37:43,046
- Oh, Dad.
- Oh, don't worry.

764
00:37:43,207 --> 00:37:45,323
I won't get in the way.
I'm just gonna grab a beer.

765
00:37:45,487 --> 00:37:47,125
Well, it's no trouble at all, Dad.

766
00:37:51,807 --> 00:37:54,640
- Dad, you and Sherry...
- Oh, jeez, I don't believe this.

767
00:37:54,807 --> 00:37:57,958
Frasier, it's over.
She's gone. She's out of my life.

768
00:37:59,447 --> 00:38:01,085
What the hell's she doing here?

769
00:38:01,247 --> 00:38:04,000
Look, she came in to borrow
the powder room. I'll be right back.

770
00:38:04,247 --> 00:38:05,236
How's everything out here?

771
00:38:05,407 --> 00:38:06,999
- Fine.
- How's everything in there?

772
00:38:07,167 --> 00:38:09,806
Fine, fine. I think I just...
I need a few more minutes.

773
00:38:09,967 --> 00:38:11,400
Were you through
with the powder room?

774
00:38:11,567 --> 00:38:13,000
Oh, sure, it's all yours.

775
00:38:13,167 --> 00:38:15,317
Oh, Frasier,
take all the time you need.

776
00:38:15,487 --> 00:38:17,205
- Yes. Thanks.
- I'll entertain your friend.

777
00:38:17,367 --> 00:38:19,517
Oh, what? And miss
this fabulous sunset?

778
00:38:21,367 --> 00:38:23,085
SHERRY:
Oh, yeah. Look at that.

779
00:38:23,247 --> 00:38:25,442
FRASIER: Yes.
- I forgot how beautiful it is.

780
00:38:25,607 --> 00:38:27,120
Yes. So it is. Yeah.

781
00:38:27,287 --> 00:38:28,720
Oh, right. Here.

782
00:38:29,967 --> 00:38:32,322
To poss... Oh, what am I doing?
Here.

783
00:38:33,887 --> 00:38:35,445
All right, just enjoy yourself.

784
00:38:35,607 --> 00:38:37,165
Two minutes. No more.

785
00:38:37,327 --> 00:38:39,716
Oh, not you, Leslie.

786
00:38:41,287 --> 00:38:44,165
I don't know what you think you're
doing, but go back and get rid of her.

787
00:38:44,327 --> 00:38:46,795
- Dad, I am not trying to torture you.
- You're doing a bad job.

788
00:38:46,967 --> 00:38:49,356
All right, listen. I'm a little
bit confused about something.

789
00:38:49,527 --> 00:38:50,880
Maybe you can help
me understand it.

790
00:38:51,047 --> 00:38:53,003
You say you don't have any
feelings for this woman.

791
00:38:53,167 --> 00:38:56,523
Why is it that the last three months
you've been happier than you've been

792
00:38:56,687 --> 00:38:58,837
- since Mom died?
- You leave your mother out of this.

793
00:38:59,487 --> 00:39:02,126
- I didn't mean to bring her into it.
- Well, good.

794
00:39:02,287 --> 00:39:04,517
Dad, is that what
this is about? Mom?

795
00:39:04,687 --> 00:39:06,678
- No. All right?
- Listen, I'm a psychiatrist...

796
00:39:06,847 --> 00:39:09,042
I don't need a psychiatrist,
and I don't need your help.

797
00:39:09,207 --> 00:39:11,721
- That is just classic defensiveness.
- Would you just drop it?

798
00:39:11,887 --> 00:39:13,400
- No, I won't drop it.
- I said drop it!

799
00:39:13,567 --> 00:39:16,035
Listen, Dad, will you...?

800
00:39:16,847 --> 00:39:18,803
Excuse me. Butterfingers.

801
00:39:19,047 --> 00:39:20,685
<i>Momentito.</i>

802
00:39:21,527 --> 00:39:23,006
Now listen, Dad, l...

803
00:39:23,167 --> 00:39:25,397
I do not mean to upset you.

804
00:39:25,567 --> 00:39:27,842
I have a feeling that what
you're going through here is

805
00:39:28,007 --> 00:39:30,760
feelings of guilt.
It's probably natural to feel that way.

806
00:39:30,927 --> 00:39:32,918
My God, I understand
what you're going through.

807
00:39:33,087 --> 00:39:35,965
No, you don't. No, you don't.
You don't understand at all.

808
00:39:37,007 --> 00:39:39,567
When you've been married
for 35 years,

809
00:39:40,047 --> 00:39:42,766
you'd never thought
there'd be anybody else.

810
00:39:43,607 --> 00:39:47,395
Then one day you hear yourself say,
"I love you," to another woman.

811
00:39:48,367 --> 00:39:51,518
Well, maybe then you'll understand
what I'm going through.

812
00:39:55,087 --> 00:39:58,477
Dad, there was a time back when
my first marriage was breaking up.

813
00:39:58,647 --> 00:40:00,046
I was talking to Mom.

814
00:40:00,207 --> 00:40:02,437
She said, "You've gotta promise
you're not gonna give up."

815
00:40:02,607 --> 00:40:04,882
I said, "The last thing I
wanna hear is a bunch of clichës

816
00:40:05,047 --> 00:40:07,436
about how we're all put on this
Earth to love one another,

817
00:40:07,607 --> 00:40:10,599
and how it's certainly possible for the
heart to love more than one person."

818
00:40:11,207 --> 00:40:13,038
I said, "All right, Mom,
give me one good reason

819
00:40:13,207 --> 00:40:15,960
for me to ever let myself
fall in love again."

820
00:40:16,247 --> 00:40:18,317
She said, "Because I said so,
and I'm your mother."

821
00:40:23,207 --> 00:40:26,279
Yeah, it sure doesn't help reminding
me what a great lady she was.

822
00:40:26,447 --> 00:40:27,721
Well,

823
00:40:27,887 --> 00:40:30,924
does it help to remind you that
Sherry's a pretty great lady too?

824
00:40:31,967 --> 00:40:34,435
God, Dad, she makes you happy.

825
00:40:35,367 --> 00:40:38,245
Niles and I would give anything
to have what you have.

826
00:40:38,607 --> 00:40:41,405
Well, not what you have
but what you have.

827
00:40:43,967 --> 00:40:46,162
Yeah, she is a pretty great lady,
isn't she?

828
00:40:47,007 --> 00:40:49,999
I don't know.
She'd probably be better off

829
00:40:50,167 --> 00:40:52,727
with some guy who wasn't
going through all this stuff.

830
00:40:52,887 --> 00:40:55,162
Well, don't you think you
ought to let her decide that?

831
00:41:15,607 --> 00:41:16,881
Hi.

832
00:41:17,727 --> 00:41:19,479
Hi.

833
00:41:25,407 --> 00:41:27,637
Well, it looks like those two
could use a little privacy.

834
00:41:27,807 --> 00:41:30,367
Do you mind if I take you
to the restaurant a little early?

835
00:41:30,527 --> 00:41:32,245
- I think that's a good idea.
FRASIER: Okay.

836
00:41:32,407 --> 00:41:35,001
We can finish up with wine later.
I mean... Well, not that I mean

837
00:41:35,167 --> 00:41:36,486
we're gonna be
coming back here.

838
00:41:36,647 --> 00:41:38,285
Not that I'm averse
to that, of course.

839
00:41:38,447 --> 00:41:40,199
I mean, if you're in the mood
for a nightgown.

840
00:41:42,247 --> 00:41:43,965
Nightcap.

841
00:41:44,687 --> 00:41:47,247
It looks like your dad and his
girlfriend are patching things up.

842
00:41:47,407 --> 00:41:48,396
FRASIER:
Yes.

843
00:41:48,767 --> 00:41:51,918
Gee, I can't thank you enough for
being tolerant about the time delay.

844
00:41:52,087 --> 00:41:54,681
LESLIE: Oh, no problem.
- Look, you'd be surprised.

845
00:41:54,847 --> 00:41:58,157
I mean, lately women just fly
into rages of intolerance

846
00:41:58,327 --> 00:42:01,285
just at the slightest provocation.
Well, shall we?

847
00:42:01,447 --> 00:42:03,915
Wait, Leslie, before you go,
I want to say something.

848
00:42:04,087 --> 00:42:06,396
Oh, good Lord. Step lively.

849
00:42:07,047 --> 00:42:11,404
Listen, you are a lucky girl to be
with someone as sweet as Frasier.

850
00:42:11,567 --> 00:42:14,286
He just did a real nice thing
for his dad and me.

851
00:42:14,767 --> 00:42:16,041
Thank you, Sherry.

852
00:42:16,207 --> 00:42:17,720
Off we go.

853
00:42:17,967 --> 00:42:19,241
We'll ride down with you.

854
00:42:19,407 --> 00:42:21,602
We're going down the street
to get a little Chinese.

855
00:42:21,767 --> 00:42:23,405
- Well, why don't we give you a lift?
- No.

856
00:42:23,567 --> 00:42:25,239
Don't you think the walk
would do them good?

857
00:42:25,407 --> 00:42:28,444
Oh, no, I think it's starting to rain.
Come on, you'll ride with us.

858
00:42:28,607 --> 00:42:31,041
Oh, you are such a doll.

859
00:42:31,207 --> 00:42:33,926
- So, Leslie, what do you do?
LESLIE: Oh, I'm a dermatologist.

860
00:42:34,087 --> 00:42:36,157
Good news, Frasier.
If you get lucky tonight,

861
00:42:36,327 --> 00:42:39,080
- she might look at that rash of yours.
FRASIER: Yep.

862
00:42:39,607 --> 00:42:41,757
SHERRY:
Oh, that reminds me of a great joke.

863
00:42:41,927 --> 00:42:45,044
No! Just hold the elevator
for me, will you?

864
00:42:45,207 --> 00:42:47,038
Eddie?

865
00:42:51,007 --> 00:42:54,204
Well, you could at least
act surprised.

